AUDIO: 'To build a working digital twin, you can scan the space once with Polycam, and the result is a 3D model, a dimensioned 2D floor plan, and a structured spatial report, all from the same walkthrough, all ready before you leave the building.'

[00:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'So, what\'s missing from most digital twin programs? Well, most of them produce a 3D model and stop there. The 3D model shows you what the space looks like, but it can\'t tell you the square footage of a room or where a renovation'

[00:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'scope starts or the fixture count on that floor. Those answers live in the 2D floor plan. And if it wasn\'t captured at the same time as the 3D model, then someone has to go back and get it'

[00:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'separately or those numbers never even exist in the digital twin at all. A digital twin with a 3D model but no floor plan is a visualization. It can be viewed, but it can\'t be queried. For a'

[00:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'facilities manager running maintenance scopes, an architect coordinating a renovation, or a contractor building a takeoff, that\'s not a twin. That\'s a fancy photo. So, why does a floor plan'

